The MIT license above covers the ferrite.js player: everything under src/, the
engine glue (engine/ferrite.c, engine/ferrite.h), the build scripts, the tests,
the demo, and the Emscripten-generated loader assets/ferrite.mjs.

This package ADDITIONALLY vendors a prebuilt, FFmpeg-derived WebAssembly engine,
assets/ferrite.wasm. That binary is a derivative work of FFmpeg and is therefore
distributed under the terms of the GNU Lesser General Public License, version
2.1 or later (LGPL-2.1-or-later) — NOT under the MIT license. The engine is
built from a purpose-built FFmpeg 8.1.1 decode subset configured WITHOUT
--enable-gpl and WITHOUT --enable-nonfree (see engine/build-engine.sh for the
exact configure flags), so it contains no GPL or non-free components; LGPL-2.1
is the operative license for the engine. The full LGPL-2.1 text is provided at
engine/COPYING.LGPLv2.1. FFmpeg's own copyright notices live in the FFmpeg
sources fetched by the build script.

Relinking (LGPL-2.1, Section 6): the engine is statically linked into a single
.wasm. To honor the user's right to modify the LGPL library and relink, this
repository ships the complete means to rebuild the engine against a modified
FFmpeg — the engine C source (engine/ferrite.c, engine/ferrite.h), the
self-contained build script with the full configure flags
(engine/build-engine.sh), and the pinned FFmpeg version (engine/ffmpeg-version).
Running engine/build-engine.sh reproduces the matched assets/ferrite.{mjs,wasm}
pair. The source repository is available at the project's public home.

Patent notice (independent of the copyright license above): the decoders bundled
in the engine (HEVC/H.264/MPEG-2 video; AAC/AC-3/E-AC-3/MP2/MP3 audio) implement
formats that may be covered by patents in some jurisdictions. Copyright
licensing under LGPL-2.1 does not grant any patent license; evaluating patent
obligations is the redistributor's responsibility. "FFmpeg" is a trademark of
Fabrice Bellard, originator of the FFmpeg project.
